WEBVTT

00:01.393 --> 00:04.194
-♪<i> Look up there</i> ♪
-♪<i> What do you see?</i> ♪

00:04.196 --> 00:05.579
♪<i> Nature and stuff</i> ♪

00:05.731 --> 00:07.080
-♪<i> Like a rock</i> ♪
-♪<i> And a tree</i> ♪

00:07.233 --> 00:09.916
♪<i> Oh, the Great North</i> ♪

00:10.069 --> 00:13.587
♪<i> Way up here,</i>
<i> you can breathe the air</i> ♪

00:13.739 --> 00:14.738
♪<i> Catch some fish</i> ♪

00:14.831 --> 00:16.406
♪<i> Or gaze at a bear</i> ♪

00:16.467 --> 00:17.574
♪<i> Wow</i> ♪

00:17.667 --> 00:21.020
♪<i> Oh, the Great North</i> ♪

00:21.171 --> 00:22.262
♪<i> Here we live, oh, oh</i> ♪

00:22.414 --> 00:23.930
♪<i> Here we'll stay, oh, whoo</i> ♪

00:24.083 --> 00:25.415
♪<i> From longest night</i>
<i> to longest day</i> ♪

00:25.434 --> 00:29.445
♪<i> In the Great North.</i> ♪

00:36.037 --> 00:37.611
(alarms ringing)

00:37.763 --> 00:39.371
(both yawn)

00:40.041 --> 00:41.448
BOTH: Chore Chiefs!

00:41.542 --> 00:43.858
And now let us say
the Chore Chiefs oath.

00:43.952 --> 00:45.193
BOTH: As the sun appears,

00:45.212 --> 00:48.863
we gather our gear,
and so our chores begin.

00:48.957 --> 00:50.865
Dish divas!

00:50.959 --> 00:53.034
Window wizards!

00:53.054 --> 00:55.471
Vacuum velociraptors!

00:56.965 --> 00:58.891
Poopin' princes!

00:59.042 --> 01:01.118
I'll tell Dad
about that one when I'm done.

01:01.136 --> 01:03.896
Let us chore no more
until tomorrow.

01:04.047 --> 01:05.731
It's time for...

01:05.882 --> 01:07.457
BOTH: Breakfast boys!

01:07.476 --> 01:10.069
Good morning,
guest house squatters.

01:10.220 --> 01:12.404
JK. I just learned about JK.

01:12.556 --> 01:15.407
-Joshing kindly.
-Guys, huge news over here.

01:15.634 --> 01:18.077
Last night, Honeybee and I
were at the Gazebo Depot--

01:18.228 --> 01:21.154
you know, gazebo gazing--
and we ran into Mayor Peppers.

01:21.307 --> 01:22.897
We told him about our new
video event company,

01:22.917 --> 01:25.642
-Pause for Applause.
-And he said he might hire us

01:25.735 --> 01:29.571
as videographers for his most
beloved niece's birthday party!

01:29.590 --> 01:33.092
Oh, I can't believe that little
Becky Peppers is already 37.

01:33.243 --> 01:36.653
Sounds like opportunity has
mounted the porch and knocked.

01:36.672 --> 01:38.171
Well, it's not our job yet.

01:38.307 --> 01:39.823
Mayor Peppers wants
to see what we can do

01:39.842 --> 01:41.491
with a lower-stakes
project first.

01:41.510 --> 01:44.494
Yup. He wants us to make a video
tribute to our beloved town

01:44.513 --> 01:46.179
for everyone to see
at the annual

01:46.332 --> 01:48.682
State of the Moose:
Lone Moose Moose Banquet.

01:48.834 --> 01:52.277
Is it time for the
S-O-T-M-L-double M-B already?

01:52.429 --> 01:55.339
I can't wait to celebrate
all the great new developments

01:55.357 --> 01:56.764
in Lone Moose this year.

01:56.784 --> 01:59.934
Like the new dog-poop bag
station near the merry-go-round.

01:59.954 --> 02:01.286
It's gorgeous.

02:01.438 --> 02:03.605
And the taxidermied bear
at the library

02:03.699 --> 02:05.031
that finally got restuffed.

02:05.184 --> 02:06.700
Nice smooth belly, no lumps.

02:06.852 --> 02:09.777
Or the new cuckoo clock factory
that's moving here.

02:09.797 --> 02:12.356
It's going
to create over 12 jobs.

02:12.449 --> 02:14.191
13. 13 jobs.

02:14.209 --> 02:16.135
(scoffs)
Hope you guys like traffic.

02:16.286 --> 02:17.544
<i> HAM:</i>
<i> Cream corn day?</i>

02:17.696 --> 02:19.696
More like dream corn day,

02:19.789 --> 02:21.214
because I got two helpings.

02:21.308 --> 02:23.475
(high-pitched):
<i> Hot!</i> Ow! Ow! Ow!

02:23.702 --> 02:25.144
Oh, no. Ham!
I'll get you some ice.

02:25.371 --> 02:27.587
Aah. Thanks, Judy. Ooh.

02:27.739 --> 02:30.374
Uh, hi, Principal Gibbons.
Sorry I yelled so loud.

02:30.467 --> 02:33.134
-Am I in trouble?
-You? Ham Tobin?

02:33.228 --> 02:35.303
Three-time Good Behavior Award
Champion?

02:35.322 --> 02:38.473
God, no. I just wanted
to make sure you're okay.

02:38.492 --> 02:41.142
Oh, I'm okay. A lot of it
pooled in my pockets.

02:41.162 --> 02:42.477
I'll just dump it out
when I get home.

02:42.496 --> 02:45.813
Sounds good.
Ham Tobin in trouble.

02:45.833 --> 02:47.958
Sheesh.
(laughs)

02:49.336 --> 02:52.320
Dang it. Now the smell of
my pants is gonna make me hungry

02:52.339 --> 02:54.247
-all day.
-Oh. Hey, Ham.

02:54.400 --> 02:55.916
Oh. Hello, cool.
I mean Quay.

02:56.068 --> 02:57.234
I saw what happened back there.

02:57.252 --> 02:58.343
I mean, actually, I heard it.

02:58.495 --> 03:01.238
-Oh, the scream?
-Don't be embarrassed.

03:01.256 --> 03:02.664
-It sounded awesome.
-Really? Thanks.

03:02.683 --> 03:04.999
I'm not even the best yeller
in my family.

03:05.019 --> 03:07.335
My brother Wolf
is the real scream queen.

03:07.354 --> 03:09.021
Well, it gave me an idea.
I was wondering

03:09.172 --> 03:11.839
if you want to try out for my
punk band, Messengers of Chaos.

03:11.859 --> 03:15.585
I used to be the singer, but I
just got into madrigal choir so,

03:15.604 --> 03:19.089
♪<i> I can't risk</i>
<i> the vocal strain.</i> ♪

03:19.107 --> 03:20.590
Anyway, the band
is pretty hard-core,

03:20.609 --> 03:22.517
so I don't know
if that's your scene.

03:22.536 --> 03:25.595
Huh. I'm hard-core sometimes.
I think.

03:25.614 --> 03:27.447
Cool. You want
to audition after school?

03:27.599 --> 03:29.208
Uh, I don't know.
(short chuckle)

03:29.435 --> 03:31.210
Is it necessary
to change vacuum attachments

03:31.361 --> 03:33.286
to properly clean corners?
(chuckles)

03:33.439 --> 03:35.214
-What?
-Yes. My answer is yes.

03:35.365 --> 03:36.531
<i> QUAY:</i>
<i> Ham, this is</i>

03:36.550 --> 03:37.883
Bethany Bones and Steven

03:38.110 --> 03:39.051
-the Psycho.
-Hey.
-What's up, man?

03:39.202 --> 03:40.444
Okay, sing this

03:40.462 --> 03:42.128
like you just got burned
by creamed corn.

03:42.281 --> 03:44.205
-But in your soul.
-Hello, my punks.

03:44.225 --> 03:46.874
My dad was wondering
if you could not practice today.

03:46.894 --> 03:49.427
He just got his appendix out,
and he says he needs to rest.

03:49.654 --> 03:52.046
Maybe we're the ones
who need a rest. From his rules.

03:52.066 --> 03:54.233
Parents are the worst.
Gill,

03:54.384 --> 03:55.809
do you want
to be our manager or not?

03:55.961 --> 03:57.143
Uh, yeah, totally,

03:57.238 --> 03:59.571
I'm your guy, 1,000%.

03:59.798 --> 04:01.131
I'll talk to him.

04:01.224 --> 04:03.891
He's kind of in and out,
but I'll-I'll try.

04:03.911 --> 04:06.245
All right, let's rock.

04:06.396 --> 04:07.579
One, two, three, four.

04:07.731 --> 04:10.231
(speaking song):
♪<i> Anarchy Stew, Anarchy Stew</i> ♪

04:10.251 --> 04:12.476
♪<i> Heat it up, add some glue...</i> ♪

04:12.494 --> 04:16.313
Come on, man. Fight society's
expectations with your voice.

04:16.331 --> 04:19.574
♪<i> Anarchy Stew,</i>
<i> the recipe's invalid</i> ♪

04:19.668 --> 04:22.652
♪<i> Now wash it down</i>
<i> with some chaos</i> ♪

04:22.746 --> 04:26.914
♪<i> Salad...</i> ♪

04:26.934 --> 04:28.583
Salad.

04:28.602 --> 04:31.161
<i> WOLF:</i>
<i> Okay, guys, this movie</i>
<i> is our chance to wow</i>

04:31.179 --> 04:33.105
-everyone in town.
-We want you all to be in it,

04:33.256 --> 04:34.697
and we're also
the kind of directors

04:34.699 --> 04:37.834
who think good ideas can
come from anywhere, like McG.

04:37.853 --> 04:39.111
So put up your umbrellas.

04:39.338 --> 04:40.928
I feel a brainstorm coming on.

04:41.023 --> 04:42.114
Let's hear those ideas.

04:42.265 --> 04:44.341
Two words.
Tree karate.

04:44.359 --> 04:45.859
Three words.
I love it.

04:46.011 --> 04:47.286
I could show the camera

04:47.513 --> 04:49.029
how to make my favorite salad.

04:49.123 --> 04:50.289
A lettuce salad.

04:50.516 --> 04:53.125
Lettuce... celebrate
that great idea.

04:53.276 --> 04:55.294
Hmm, and what will I do?

04:55.445 --> 04:57.629
I don't know.
Just off the top of my head...

04:57.781 --> 05:00.357
Uh, a dead ballerina
wandering through a rainy field

05:00.375 --> 05:01.858
looking for
her lover of yesteryear.

05:01.877 --> 05:04.285
And then she does a dance
to help her process the fact

05:04.305 --> 05:06.305
that everyone and everything
she knew is gone.

05:06.532 --> 05:08.715
Wow. How can we say no
to any of these ideas

05:08.867 --> 05:09.975
when they're all so good?

05:10.126 --> 05:11.310
We can't.
We're not insane.

05:11.419 --> 05:13.145
Now let the magic commence.

05:13.372 --> 05:15.055
Wonderful.
I'll go get my lettuce.

05:15.149 --> 05:17.131
And my lettuce bowl.

05:17.151 --> 05:18.650
That was pretty intense
in there.

05:18.802 --> 05:21.987
It was as intense as the last
time I got to see my grandpa.

05:22.138 --> 05:24.548
Two weeks ago.
He was super grumpy.

05:24.641 --> 05:27.717
Ham, your voice made me furious.
In a great way.

05:27.736 --> 05:30.403
Thanks, but just so you know,
I can't really sing that loud.

05:30.497 --> 05:32.313
The microphone
was making me louder.

05:32.407 --> 05:34.558
Well, we have a lot of people
who want the job,

05:34.651 --> 05:35.909
so we'll let you know.

05:36.003 --> 05:37.243
Thanks for the opportunity.

05:37.396 --> 05:39.896
Quay.
Stephen the Psycho.

05:39.915 --> 05:42.031
Bethany Bones.
Gill.

05:42.843 --> 05:44.250
-♪ ♪
-♪<i> Sad ballerina</i> ♪

05:44.345 --> 05:45.735
♪<i> Sad ballerina, sad</i> ♪

05:45.754 --> 05:47.846
♪<i> Why, ballerina,</i>
<i> why, ballerina, why?</i> ♪

05:47.997 --> 05:49.348
And cut.

05:49.575 --> 05:51.575
We got 20 minutes of
Judy doing that. Is that enough?

05:51.593 --> 05:54.335
Not sure. You know, the best
movies shot tons of footage

05:54.429 --> 05:56.021
'cause they made it up
as they went along.

05:56.248 --> 05:58.357
<i> Jurassic Park</i> was originally
a teen romantic comedy

05:58.508 --> 06:01.008
called<i> Jungle High,</i>
but it was so darn boring,

06:01.028 --> 06:02.435
they started adding dinosaurs.

06:02.529 --> 06:04.270
Who knows
what we'll end up with.

06:04.423 --> 06:06.531
All right.
Judy, from the top.

06:06.683 --> 06:08.592
-♪<i> Sad ballerina,</i>
<i> sad ballerina</i> ♪
-(phone ringing)

06:08.726 --> 06:10.276
-♪<i> Sad, why, ballerina</i> ♪
-HAM: I got it!

06:10.429 --> 06:11.945
-♪<i> Why, ballerina?</i> ♪
-Hello?

06:12.097 --> 06:13.930
(gasps)
I did? I am?!

06:13.949 --> 06:17.250
I'm in a band! Bring in the Ham,
bring in the punk.

06:24.367 --> 06:26.551
Huh. Where's the button bin?

06:26.703 --> 06:27.886
Ah! Aha.

06:28.113 --> 06:31.038
'Kay, let's see what says
"hard-core."

06:31.133 --> 06:33.058
No, nope, nope, not you.

06:33.209 --> 06:34.726
There you are.

06:34.953 --> 06:36.786
Yeah. Punk rock.

06:36.805 --> 06:39.714
So, uh, what time
are we practicing?

06:39.733 --> 06:41.641
Oh, today isn't a practice day.

06:41.793 --> 06:43.977
Every Tuesday, we go punkin'.

06:44.071 --> 06:45.737
Yeah, we go do badass stuff

06:45.889 --> 06:48.055
to inspire us
to write badass songs.

06:48.075 --> 06:50.133
Mm-hmm, we live the punk way
of life,

06:50.226 --> 06:51.818
like Johnny Rotten
or Gwen Stefani.

06:51.970 --> 06:55.321
So are we doing stuff that could
actually get us in trouble?

06:55.416 --> 06:57.416
Do you want to wake up in
a coffin at the end of your life

06:57.643 --> 06:59.492
with a report card
full of straight A's

06:59.645 --> 07:01.811
and a bunch
of pleasant memories?

07:01.905 --> 07:03.070
No?

07:03.165 --> 07:04.589
Punk or die, butterfly.

07:04.741 --> 07:06.741
♪<i> Go to sleep,</i>
<i> teachers and guppies</i> ♪

07:06.760 --> 07:09.744
♪<i> You can't stop us from</i>
<i> petting those puppies...</i> ♪

07:09.763 --> 07:11.004
Engine to Starbase.

07:11.156 --> 07:12.914
This is Private John Seinfeld.

07:12.933 --> 07:14.841
I see no sign
of a breach anywhere.

07:14.993 --> 07:16.660
Aah!

07:16.678 --> 07:18.828
♪<i> 'Cause it's just chalk, but</i>
<i>look what we wrote with chalk</i> ♪

07:18.847 --> 07:21.514
♪<i> We'll never be like you,</i>
<i> we wrote the word "poo"</i> ♪

07:21.667 --> 07:24.017
♪<i> And you can't stop us,</i>
<i> no way...</i> ♪

07:24.169 --> 07:25.593
Before you begin,

07:25.612 --> 07:27.428
check and make sure
you didn't buy cabbage.

07:27.448 --> 07:29.673
♪<i> Doing stuff to mannequins</i> ♪

07:29.766 --> 07:31.283
♪<i> Getting all</i>
<i> straight A's again</i> ♪

07:31.434 --> 07:33.677
♪<i> So punk we'll</i>
<i> make your freezer melt</i> ♪

07:33.695 --> 07:36.179
♪<i> Wearing extra seat belts</i> ♪

07:36.198 --> 07:38.348
♪<i> You said "take one"</i>
<i> but we'll take three</i> ♪

07:38.366 --> 07:40.850
♪<i> And now we're sitting</i>
<i> in a frozen crowd of trees.</i> ♪

07:40.944 --> 07:44.354
God, my mom is smothering me.

07:44.372 --> 07:46.206
I know I have a viola lesson.

07:46.358 --> 07:47.966
You know what? I'm gonna show up
five minutes late

07:48.117 --> 07:49.526
to mess with her head.

07:49.544 --> 07:51.194
When my mom asks me
if anything interesting happened

07:51.213 --> 07:53.530
at school today,
I'm gonna say no.

07:53.548 --> 07:56.457
But it's a lie. Tons
of interesting things happened.

07:56.477 --> 07:59.144
My mom is making us spaghetti
and garlic bread<i> again.</i>

07:59.295 --> 08:00.479
I can't wait to tell her

08:00.630 --> 08:02.647
how I spoiled my appetite
with baby carrots.

08:02.799 --> 08:04.816
So you guys, uh,
<i> don't</i> get along

08:04.968 --> 08:06.318
with your parents really well

08:06.545 --> 08:07.468
and love spending time
with them?

08:07.562 --> 08:09.470
What? Of course not.
Why? Do you?

08:09.490 --> 08:11.990
Uh, no. I mean,
sometimes my dad gets me up

08:12.217 --> 08:14.141
to do chores at 5:30 a.m.,
and I'm like,

08:14.236 --> 08:15.568
I don't even love doing chores
or bonding

08:15.721 --> 08:17.737
with my dad more than anything
in the world. (sputters)

08:17.831 --> 08:19.572
-(phone dings)
-Ugh. Come on, Mom.

08:19.725 --> 08:21.833
You don't control me.
See you later, guys.

08:21.985 --> 08:23.668
-Stay punk.
-I will.

08:23.820 --> 08:25.319
I... will.

08:26.507 --> 08:29.174
Hello there, Ham. Better hang up
your coat and wash your hands--

08:29.401 --> 08:30.825
we're eating in front
of<i> Wheel of Fortune.</i>

08:30.919 --> 08:32.402
It's Teachers Week.

08:32.495 --> 08:34.012
<i> QUAY:</i>
<i> Parents are the worst...</i>
<i> the worst...</i>

08:34.163 --> 08:35.663
<i> STEVEN:</i>
<i> Spaghetti and garlic</i>
<i> bread</i> again.

08:35.682 --> 08:38.833
Ham, did you hear me?
Can you wash your hands?

08:38.927 --> 08:41.077
<i> You</i> wash my hands.

08:41.096 --> 08:43.188
Uh... it was just a suggestion.

08:43.339 --> 08:45.690
You know your own hands.

08:47.528 --> 08:49.602
Whoops. It seems like
you accidentally

08:49.755 --> 08:51.345
missed the coat hook there.

08:51.439 --> 08:54.941
Or-- I don't know-- maybe
I laid my jacket carelessly

08:55.093 --> 08:56.276
on the ground on purpose.

08:56.428 --> 08:58.945
Come on, bud. Are you low
on potassium again?

08:59.097 --> 09:00.872
Do you need a banana?

09:01.024 --> 09:03.433
No, thank you.

09:03.451 --> 09:06.770
Do you know you put a banana
on your coat, son?

09:06.788 --> 09:08.772
Yeah, Dad, I do.

09:08.790 --> 09:09.956
Okay.

09:10.108 --> 09:11.716
(groans)

09:11.868 --> 09:13.943
I just don't feel like

09:13.962 --> 09:16.780
hanging my jacket, okay?!

09:16.798 --> 09:18.448
We're back on the jacket.

09:18.466 --> 09:20.116
Sometimes when you tell me
to do something,

09:20.135 --> 09:22.543
uh, I don't feel like doing it.

09:22.637 --> 09:24.211
And you know what else?

09:24.231 --> 09:25.713
I'm... I'm quitting
Chore Chiefs.

09:25.732 --> 09:27.065
At least for a day.

09:27.216 --> 09:28.733
-Then we'll see.
-Whoa.

09:28.960 --> 09:30.960
Hmm. Well,
this is new territory for us,

09:30.979 --> 09:34.964
but I guess I should punish you
or something for acting out?

09:35.058 --> 09:37.300
Maybe go
take a break in your room.

09:37.319 --> 09:39.369
Fine!

09:40.972 --> 09:43.139
Do you want to help me finish
setting up the TV trays?

09:43.232 --> 09:44.916
Sure. Where is everybody?

09:45.143 --> 09:46.993
Don't they know
it's Teachers Week on<i> Wheel?</i>

09:47.145 --> 09:48.995
I'd like
to solve the puzzle, Moon.

09:49.147 --> 09:52.090
"I forgot to remind them."

09:52.759 --> 09:54.259
These candy corn lights
are like, "What?

09:54.486 --> 09:55.985
It's not Halloween, right?"

09:56.079 --> 09:58.504
My dumb dad said they were cheap
and a fire hazard,

09:58.657 --> 10:01.082
so he wouldn't let me hang them
at our house.

10:01.101 --> 10:03.009
I'm so sorry, Quay.

10:03.161 --> 10:04.661
(sighs)
Thanks, Bethany.

10:04.679 --> 10:07.588
Yeah, my, uh, my dad
sent me to my room last night

10:07.682 --> 10:09.999
because I said I didn't
want to do chores anymore.

10:10.093 --> 10:11.592
And I was in there
for 45 minutes

10:11.612 --> 10:14.671
-before my sister came
and got me for dessert.
-Damn.

10:14.689 --> 10:16.097
Yeah.
It's kind of like...

10:16.191 --> 10:17.616
Parents-- don't they know
that they're jerks?

10:17.843 --> 10:21.361
G-Getting on my case,
making me do homework?

10:21.513 --> 10:24.105
Wait.
Say that again.

10:25.200 --> 10:28.126
♪<i> Parents, don't</i>
<i> they know they're jerks?</i> ♪

10:28.353 --> 10:31.354
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> make me do homework</i> ♪

10:31.373 --> 10:34.466
♪<i> Parents, they always</i>
<i> drive me nuts</i> ♪

10:34.617 --> 10:37.360
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> and they smell like</i> ♪

10:37.379 --> 10:41.197
(singing):
♪<i> Butts.</i> ♪

10:41.216 --> 10:43.141
That was, like, incredible.

10:43.292 --> 10:45.051
Hey, guys, guess what? I,

10:45.145 --> 10:47.646
Gill Beavers, your manager,
got you a gig.

10:47.873 --> 10:50.297
-Yes! -Whoa.
-Oh, hell yeah.
-Messengers Of Chaos.

10:50.317 --> 10:51.650
You guys are playing
a one-song set

10:51.801 --> 10:55.469
at The State of the Moose:
Lone Moose Moose Banquet.

10:55.489 --> 10:56.988
-Yes!
-My dad's on
the planning committee.

10:57.215 --> 10:58.398
He said he's got
to fill four minutes,

10:58.492 --> 10:59.899
and there's no budget,
so we're in.

10:59.993 --> 11:01.767
We have to play "Parents,"
for sure.

11:01.920 --> 11:02.977
It's our best song.

11:02.996 --> 11:04.570
Lone Moose is about
to get a wake-up call.

11:04.723 --> 11:08.315
Cock-a-doodle-doo.
Here comes the reality rooster.

11:08.335 --> 11:11.152
How is the videotape
coming along?

11:11.171 --> 11:14.339
Very well. We already have
35 hours of footage.

11:14.566 --> 11:15.823
Oh, hello, Ham.

11:15.917 --> 11:18.826
I assume I shouldn't ask you
about washing your hands.

11:18.845 --> 11:21.237
Uh-oh.
Here come the fireworks.

11:21.330 --> 11:23.014
That's right, Dad.
I will wash them

11:23.166 --> 11:24.349
if I want to,
which I already did.

11:24.500 --> 11:26.333
Great.
So, how was your day?

11:26.428 --> 11:28.836
Good. We had band practice
at Gill Beavers' house.

11:28.855 --> 11:31.672
Director's note: get footage
of band practice for film.

11:31.766 --> 11:34.267
Great idea, my Taika Wife-titi.

11:34.419 --> 11:36.177
(gasps)
Oh. And we have a gig.

11:36.196 --> 11:39.013
At the State of the Moose:
Lone Moose Moose Banquet.

11:39.032 --> 11:40.273
-Wonderful, son.
-Wow, holy toast!

11:40.425 --> 11:42.016
We're even gonna play
a new song I wrote.

11:42.035 --> 11:46.429
It's called "Pare... rr..."

11:46.448 --> 11:48.097
What, Ham?

11:48.116 --> 11:50.116
What is the new song
you wrote called?

11:50.268 --> 11:52.043
"Pair... of Friends."

11:52.195 --> 11:54.103
About two friends
who go on a fishing trip.

11:54.122 --> 11:55.455
(gasps)
Do they catch anything?

11:55.607 --> 11:56.789
-Yup.
-Fantastic.

11:56.942 --> 11:59.275
Oh, sick! We're headed
right into the fiery heart

11:59.368 --> 12:00.719
of the Lone Moose music scene.

12:00.870 --> 12:03.763
Hey, does Gill's dad still make
those kickass blondies?

12:08.395 --> 12:09.894
<i> (drumsticks</i>
<i> rhythmically clicking)</i>

12:10.046 --> 12:11.229
♪<i> Parents</i> ♪

12:11.380 --> 12:12.880
♪<i> Don't they know</i>
<i> they're jerks?</i> ♪

12:12.899 --> 12:15.549
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> make me do homework</i> ♪

12:15.569 --> 12:18.811
♪<i> Parents, they always</i>
<i> drive me nuts</i> ♪

12:18.964 --> 12:21.798
♪<i> Parents, and they smell like</i> ♪

12:21.891 --> 12:24.159
♪<i> Butts.</i> ♪

12:25.153 --> 12:27.370
Let's take a blondie break.

12:28.156 --> 12:30.231
So, uh, what do you think?

12:30.250 --> 12:32.325
Buddy, I'm worried
about that song.

12:32.477 --> 12:35.069
You're really going to sing that
in front of Dad at the banquet?

12:35.088 --> 12:36.329
About parents sucking?

12:36.481 --> 12:38.239
I mean, you might as well
pull out Dad's heart

12:38.258 --> 12:39.591
and whiz all over it.

12:39.742 --> 12:41.742
-He's gonna be hella crushed.
-I know.

12:41.762 --> 12:44.596
Hey, maybe you guys can write
a different song, like, uh...

12:44.747 --> 12:48.249
♪<i> Blondies, boy,</i>
<i> they taste so good.</i> ♪

12:48.268 --> 12:50.676
-Yeah, good idea, Wolf.
-Good. Great talk, buddy.

12:50.829 --> 12:52.937
Hey, when you play
the blondie song at the banquet,

12:53.164 --> 12:54.755
can you mention
I helped write it?

12:55.517 --> 12:58.501
Hey, Dad. How's
the wood-chopping coming along?

12:58.594 --> 13:01.187
(grunts)
There's still a lot more to do.

13:01.339 --> 13:04.340
-So, it's great.
-Um, I was wondering something.

13:04.359 --> 13:06.934
What would you do
if someone called you a jerk?

13:07.028 --> 13:09.436
A jerk? Ouch.
That'd be tough,

13:09.531 --> 13:12.865
especially if it was someone
I cared about and respected.

13:13.018 --> 13:15.794
But I'd probably get over it
within a matter of months.

13:15.945 --> 13:17.111
-Months, huh?
-Ham,

13:17.130 --> 13:18.797
did someone at school
call you a jerk?

13:19.024 --> 13:22.041
Is that why you put a banana
on your coat the other night?

13:22.193 --> 13:24.377
Uh, no, Dad.
No one called me a jerk.

13:24.471 --> 13:27.380
Hmm. Well, whatever it is,
I will try to help.

13:27.532 --> 13:30.624
I know I don't always understand
what you're going through,

13:30.644 --> 13:33.645
and the Chore Chiefs hasn't been
the same without you this week,

13:33.796 --> 13:36.055
but I'm glad
we're communicating.

13:36.149 --> 13:40.151
Uh, yeah.
Me, too, Dad.

13:41.396 --> 13:43.655
<i> (drumsticks</i>
<i> rhythmically clicking)</i>

13:43.882 --> 13:46.473
♪<i> Parents, don't they</i>
<i> know they're jerks?</i> ♪

13:46.568 --> 13:50.736
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> make me do homework?</i> ♪

13:50.889 --> 13:52.997
(applause, cheering)

13:57.486 --> 14:00.338
Dad?
Has anyone seen my dad?

14:00.489 --> 14:02.990
Telegram.
Telegram for Mr. Ham Tobin.

14:03.009 --> 14:05.068
(gasps)
I'm Mr. Ham Tobin.

14:05.086 --> 14:06.252
"Mr. Tobin. Stop.

14:06.404 --> 14:08.179
"We regret to inform you.
Stop.

14:08.331 --> 14:10.497
"That your father has died.
Stop.

14:10.517 --> 14:12.075
"His heart stopped.

14:12.093 --> 14:14.077
"Stop. And then exploded.

14:14.170 --> 14:16.929
"Stop. When someone
called him a jerk.

14:17.082 --> 14:18.505
Stop."

14:18.600 --> 14:20.191
No!

14:21.086 --> 14:22.101
<i> MOON:</i>
<i> Engine to Starbase.</i>

14:22.253 --> 14:23.695
Wolfie, it's 3:00
in the morning.

14:23.922 --> 14:25.104
Is everything okay?

14:25.198 --> 14:27.273
I told you not to
drink orange soda after 7:00.

14:27.367 --> 14:29.108
It's not that.
It's...

14:29.202 --> 14:31.202
Look, I know I promised
I could edit this thing,

14:31.429 --> 14:34.205
but the cut's 19 hours
and 11 minutes long.

14:34.357 --> 14:36.040
Babe, we can cut it down.

14:36.192 --> 14:39.026
How? Everything Judy did
was solid gold.

14:39.045 --> 14:41.437
And Dad. And Moon.
It's all gold.

14:41.530 --> 14:43.381
It's just one giant
gold sandwich

14:43.608 --> 14:46.700
with hundreds of slices of gold
smothered in gold sauce.

14:46.720 --> 14:48.111
Wolf, you have to relax.

14:48.129 --> 14:49.629
The first cut of
<i>Maze Runner 2: The Scorch Trials</i>

14:49.781 --> 14:51.872
was eight hours long,
and it turned out perfect.

14:51.966 --> 14:54.467
Yeah, but they had the best
people in the world working

14:54.619 --> 14:57.228
on<i> Maze Runner 2: The Scorch</i>
<i> Trials</i> and a lot of time.

14:57.455 --> 14:59.122
We have to show something
tomorrow night,

14:59.140 --> 15:00.547
and I have no idea
what it's gonna be.

15:00.567 --> 15:02.458
Babe, when John Krasinski
has a script problem

15:02.477 --> 15:05.219
who pulls out that big red pen
and goes nuts?

15:05.238 --> 15:08.055
-Ah, his wife, Emily Blunt.
-Exactly.

15:08.149 --> 15:10.700
Now, let's cut the crust off
this panini.

15:12.228 --> 15:14.913
Guys, hey, um,
about the song tonight.

15:15.064 --> 15:16.322
I was thinking about it,

15:16.474 --> 15:18.416
and I don't think "Parents"
rocks quite hard enough.

15:18.643 --> 15:20.084
Yeah, so, um, I came up

15:20.311 --> 15:22.145
with an even better song
we can play instead.

15:22.163 --> 15:24.313
(scat singing)

15:24.332 --> 15:26.315
♪<i> Butternut squash?</i>
<i> Better not, Josh.</i> ♪

15:26.334 --> 15:28.501
♪<i> Butternut squash?</i>
<i> Better not, Josh.</i> ♪

15:28.595 --> 15:31.003
Definitely brings up
some valid issues,

15:31.156 --> 15:32.597
but not totally feeling it.

15:32.748 --> 15:36.659
Yeah, I mean, that is great, but
it's not "Parents" level great.

15:36.678 --> 15:39.845
Ham, just be happy
you wrote the perfect song.

15:39.998 --> 15:42.348
-"Parents" rules.
-Mm...

15:42.500 --> 15:44.350
<i> HONEYBEE:</i>
<i> Well, it's two minutes</i>

15:44.444 --> 15:46.185
and 48 seconds of something.
I just hope it's ready.

15:46.337 --> 15:47.946
PEPPERS:
Good evening, everyone.

15:48.173 --> 15:49.338
I am Mayor Peppers, and tonight

15:49.432 --> 15:51.265
we're here to talk about
Lone Moose.

15:51.326 --> 15:53.451
But first, let us acknowledge
that before this place

15:53.602 --> 15:56.103
was called "Lone Moose"
by some very cold

15:56.122 --> 15:57.604
and very grabby Europeans,

15:57.699 --> 16:00.850
it was the homeland of my
ancestors, the Sugpiaq people,

16:00.868 --> 16:03.369
for thousands and thousands
and thousands of years.

16:03.463 --> 16:05.630
And while land acknowledgements
are fine,

16:05.781 --> 16:08.615
it'd be better if they just went
ahead and gave the land back.

16:08.635 --> 16:11.711
I'd also like to say that
I believe Vera over there

16:11.805 --> 16:13.787
took my cupcake caddy
Tupperware

16:13.881 --> 16:15.381
at last month's bingo night.

16:15.475 --> 16:18.217
So, if you feel like giving her
a disapproving head shake,

16:18.369 --> 16:19.626
by all means, go for it.

16:19.646 --> 16:22.388
And now it's time
to let the Moose loose.

16:22.540 --> 16:26.375
Later, we'll be hearing from the
CEO of the cuckoo clock factory.

16:26.394 --> 16:29.303
But first, help me welcome
Lone Moose's

16:29.397 --> 16:32.806
very first punk
rock and roll band,

16:32.826 --> 16:34.066
Messengers of Chaos,

16:34.219 --> 16:35.885
-with a youthful song.
-(applause)

16:35.903 --> 16:37.887
I wore a button today, too.

16:37.905 --> 16:39.646
And I brought both of these.

16:39.741 --> 16:41.390
Cool.

16:42.227 --> 16:43.835
-(guitar plays over speaker)
-Hi.

16:44.062 --> 16:46.838
Um, we're
Messengers of, um, Chaos,

16:46.989 --> 16:48.931
and this song is called...

16:48.933 --> 16:50.041
(mumbling):
"Parents."

16:50.193 --> 16:52.260
One, two, three, four.

16:53.496 --> 16:55.496
♪ <i> Parents, uh, parents... </i> ♪

16:55.515 --> 16:56.514
(singing gibberish)

16:56.741 --> 17:00.685
-What are you doing, man?
-(whimpering)

17:00.912 --> 17:02.687
(speaker feedback)

17:02.914 --> 17:04.004
Ham?

17:04.024 --> 17:06.173
Okay, well,
while we figure that out,

17:06.192 --> 17:08.175
let's take a moment
to meet the CEO

17:08.194 --> 17:10.570
from Elegant Cuckoos,
Paul Reingold.

17:12.106 --> 17:13.939
Cuckoo.
What do you think of

17:14.034 --> 17:15.775
when you hear the word "cuckoo"?

17:16.427 --> 17:20.163
Wrong. What you should think
is inspiration.

17:24.102 --> 17:25.768
-Ham? Hey, what's going on?
-Dad.

17:25.861 --> 17:27.027
(clears throat, sighs)

17:27.121 --> 17:28.287
I have a confession to make.

17:28.381 --> 17:29.881
I was about
to sing a terrible song

17:30.032 --> 17:31.532
about how parents are jerks,

17:31.551 --> 17:33.276
and then everyone would think
I was singing about you,

17:33.294 --> 17:36.054
including you, but it's not
even about you. Not really.

17:36.205 --> 17:38.631
Well, what do
the song words say?

17:38.783 --> 17:41.634
Hmm. You know,
just that parents are jerks

17:41.786 --> 17:44.228
and that they stink and
they're dumb and they're bossy.

17:44.380 --> 17:45.971
You know, that kind of thing.

17:46.124 --> 17:47.973
Ham, it's okay.
In fact,

17:48.126 --> 17:49.975
I have honestly been relieved

17:50.128 --> 17:51.961
to finally see
your rebellious side.

17:51.979 --> 17:55.573
I mean, you have always been
so agreeable and so helpful.

17:55.724 --> 17:57.909
You don't earn the title
Chore Chief for nothing.

17:58.060 --> 17:59.802
I love being a Chore Chief.

17:59.821 --> 18:02.822
I guess I am hard-core
about hard chores.

18:02.974 --> 18:04.323
I know you are, son.

18:04.475 --> 18:07.326
But it's okay
to explore your rebellious side.

18:07.420 --> 18:10.088
-Really?
-Yes, and I would be honored

18:10.315 --> 18:12.924
for you to sing
a disparaging song about me.

18:13.075 --> 18:15.426
-(gasps) You would?
-Very much.

18:15.653 --> 18:17.987
And if being a proud parent
makes me a jerk,

18:18.005 --> 18:20.005
then I'm the jerkiest parent
there is.

18:20.158 --> 18:21.841
You call me Beef Jerky.

18:21.935 --> 18:23.250
Thanks, Beef Jerky.

18:23.269 --> 18:26.312
Now get in there
and give me hell.

18:28.166 --> 18:29.849
Hey, sorry about that,
everybody.

18:30.001 --> 18:33.277
You know, punk rock is about
saying what you really think,

18:33.504 --> 18:34.595
no matter what.

18:34.689 --> 18:36.781
It also seems
to be about wearing army coats

18:36.932 --> 18:38.098
with lots of buttons.

18:38.118 --> 18:39.450
Honestly, I'm still learning.

18:39.602 --> 18:42.178
Anyway, this song is about
what I really think.

18:42.271 --> 18:44.163
It's called "Parents."

18:45.608 --> 18:48.292
♪<i> Parents, don't they know</i>
<i> they're neat?</i> ♪

18:48.444 --> 18:51.370
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> make the food I eat</i> ♪

18:51.522 --> 18:54.540
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> drive me to the mall</i> ♪

18:54.692 --> 18:58.118
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> buy expensive dolls</i> ♪

18:58.138 --> 19:00.972
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> they have cool careers</i> ♪

19:01.199 --> 19:04.717
♪<i> Parents,</i>
<i> help me face my fears!</i> ♪

19:05.703 --> 19:08.312
I love my dad
and I don't care who knows it.

19:08.464 --> 19:10.606
(song ends)

19:11.634 --> 19:13.300
-Hey, Ham.
-Hey, Quay.

19:13.319 --> 19:15.211
Sorry that I changed the lyrics
of our song

19:15.229 --> 19:17.229
into a song
about how I like parents.

19:17.382 --> 19:19.139
If you want to kick me out
of the band, I get it.

19:19.233 --> 19:21.492
Actually, that was
really punk rock,

19:21.644 --> 19:23.402
changing the words at
the last minute like that. Plus,

19:23.496 --> 19:27.223
my mom liked it, and she kind
of does a lot of stuff for me.

19:27.316 --> 19:30.817
And now, a very special video

19:30.837 --> 19:32.503
by Wolf and Honeybee Shaw-Tobin.

19:32.655 --> 19:35.414
Here is
<i> To Lone Moose, With Love.</i>

19:35.566 --> 19:37.583
Greta Gerwig,
give us your light.

19:37.677 --> 19:42.571
♪ <i> Why, ballerina,</i>
<i> why, ballerina, why? </i> ♪

19:42.665 --> 19:45.016
<i> And that's how you fill</i>
<i> a pitcher with water.</i>

19:45.167 --> 19:46.409
Why are they so quiet?

19:46.427 --> 19:48.019
Maybe this is just
a total disaster.

19:48.170 --> 19:50.579
Hey, that's my house!

19:50.673 --> 19:55.026
And there's the gazebo!
I've sat there.

19:56.754 --> 19:58.029
(gasps)
That's my backyard!

19:58.256 --> 19:59.271
And my werewolf mask!

19:59.365 --> 20:01.032
I lent it to them.
(laughs)

20:01.183 --> 20:03.517
-Wow.
-I recognize so many places.

20:03.536 --> 20:06.537
This is the best movie
I have ever seen.

20:06.764 --> 20:08.706
WOMAN'S VOICE:

20:09.934 --> 20:11.024
(applause)

20:11.118 --> 20:12.526
We made a masterpiece.

20:12.545 --> 20:16.214
You complete me.
And our video projects.

20:16.441 --> 20:17.940
<i> HAM:</i>
<i> The trick to writing</i>

20:17.959 --> 20:20.459
a good punk song is finding
something that you're mad about

20:20.611 --> 20:22.053
and then just
kind of shoutin' it.

20:22.204 --> 20:23.612
Huh, sounds easy enough.

20:23.706 --> 20:26.799
Let me think of something
that really makes me furious.

20:26.951 --> 20:28.375
Oh, okay, I-I have one.

